Business model conventions

In order to make all Business Models uniform and easy to understand for everyone, we define certain conventions and standards which need to be followed. This page is a summary of standards we currently have for Business Model content.

Convention Business Model

Published: 25.02.2020
Last update: 16.05.2022
Reading time: 14 minutes
Target audience: Everyone

Business Model in General

The purpose of the Business Model is to identify all Business Actors (Business Roles and Business Groups) and Business Use Cases participating in the Business Discipline. Alternatively, to identify the Processes that are logically related to, or cover, the Business Use Cases. It is also necessary to identify the Products and Intermediates involved in each process. It is also necessary to describe the links and relations between products and intermediates and their important attributes. Then, it is important to write down Business Use Case Specifications. Business Scenarios can also be an important part of Business Model. Business Scenario algorithmically describes the variants of predictable flows of certain Business Use Cases launched by business actors (business roles and business groups). uuAppBusinessModel is a business model that meets the uuP standard. The uuAppBusinessModel is finally an input product for uuAppModel, which is already an exact specification for creating an uuApp "Business Discipline" application.

More information about Business Model or uuAppBusinessModelKit can be found in uuAppBusinessModelKit Documentation.
Business Model must include everything that is neeeded to understand business issues of the application and all that the customer requires in terms of analysis.
  • Each uuApp should have a separate book for its Business Model (the book can be ordered via +4U Mall as uuBooKit).
  • Business Model has to be created with uuAppBusinessModelKit (which can be ordered via +4U Mall as uuAppBusinessModelKit).
  • The content of the Business Model book must be written in English.
  • uuAppBusinessModelKit automatically generates the structure of Business Model and the structure of each page, so it will guide you through the Business Model creation process. Nevertheless, this page can provide more information about each part of Business Model.
  • uuAppBusinessModelKit also allows you to create relations:
    1. Between Business Model entitities (e.g. a specific process and a Business Use Case, an Actor and a Business Use Case etc.).
    2. Between Business Model and Business Requests (e.g. a Business Use Case fulfills the goal of a User Story, Business Actor is related to User Story describing actor etc.). For more information visit External relations of the User Story.
    3. Between Business Model and Application Model (e.g. Business Use Case is a basis for design and implementation of use-cases like uuCommand, uu5Uve, uu5Route, uuScript etc.). For more information visit Relations between uuAppBusinessModelKit and uuAppModelKit products or section Artifact own relations and Relations from other artifacts.
Descriptions

It may seem insignificant, but descriptions and explanations are underestimated. A few clear and concise sentences can save time that would be otherwise spent on trying to figure out what something means or why we need it.

For instance, when describing a Business Use Case, you can provide the context of the Business Use Case:

  • What is the goal of the Business Use Case? What the Business Use Case does?
  • Why we need it? What is it going to solve?
  • Are there any restrictions or specific conditions that must be considered?

In the initial project phase, you may not know all of this. However, over time, it is important to supplement this information and keep it up to date.

At the same time, keep in mind to describe the most important facts and avoid endless description.

Business Discipline

Business Discipline is a defined business area logically constructed with some purpose. Business Discipline produces something that is defined like the Final Products or simply Products.
In each Business Model should be only one Business Discipline and it could be covered by one or more uuSubApplications.
What must be filled:
  • Name and description
  • Overview
    • Description of the Business Discipline (main idea, main business problem).
    • For detailed specification, related Concepts are used.
  • Dictionary
    • If there are any uncommon terms used in the Business Model, it is then needed to list their abbreviations on this page. This list of definitions is appropriate for applications meant for specific types of business issues.
    • Keep this dictionary up to date.
    • Note that every term used in the Business Model should be here.
    • It is highly recommended to use the uuBookKit function Dictionary here (and further use these terms via quotations).
  • uuP Classification
    • The diagram below shows the uuP Business Discipline relation to the Business Discipline and its hierarchy in uuP Methodology.
    • More information about uuP can be found at Unicorn Universe Process Methodology.
    • Examples:
      • uuAppBusinessModelKit Business Discipline
      • uuChargeUp CPO Business Discipline
  • uuBml Stencil
    • Each uuApp should have its own uuBml stencil. A stencil is usually a subject of internal directions.
    • More information can be found at How to get uuBml stencil.
    • uuBml Stencil must be done in the design phase of a product.

Concepts

The Concept is a document, which provides description of important thing, explanation of the problem or solution of the specific issue. Each Concept is related to the Business Discipline.
Concepts are optional. A concept is not needed if the Business Discipline has been described well in the Overview.
It serves as an explanation for individual business parts, new features etc.
In case product should be connected to uuTerritory, concept uuBt (or uuTerritory) structure is mandatory. It should provide information how many uuAwsc can be in given territory, where uuObcs should be located (defined or not-defined place) etc.

What must be filled:
  • Name and description
  • Concept content - specific description of the concept. The structure is not standardized.

Processes

Process represents a series of actions or steps taken in order to achieve a particular end. It logically relates to and frames Business Use Cases (the actions and the steps). During the process, Input Products are consumed to be converted to output products. The output products can serve as an input for the next steps of a process as Intermediate Products or, they can be the products of the final steps of a process fulfilling all desired requests of quality and quantity - Final Products.
There is always one main process in uuAppBusinessModel.
The main process, which covers all processes of the described Business Discipline, is described on the Processes page.

What must be filled:
  • Name and description
  • Process Diagram
    • First level decomposition of processes with hierarchical classification and its relations (e.g. one process precedes another process etc.).
    • "Start" and "End" are mandatory processes.
    • Examples:
      • uclGoodymat - Processes
      • uuSolutionExchange - Processes

Process

What must be filled:
  • Name and description
  • Process - Product Diagram
    • From this diagram, it must be clear which products are related to this specific process.
      • E.g. process Order management includes products Order and Payment.
  • Business Use Case List
    • A list of use cases included in this process.
    • Each process must contain at least one Business Use Case.
  • Business Use Case List Diagram (not mandatory)
    • Diagram of Business Use Cases included in this specific process.
    • For better understanding, they can be divided into specific areas etc.
    • Actors can be assigned to specific Business Use Cases or groups of Business Use Cases.
  • Business Scenario List (not mandatory)
    • List of related Business Scenarios.
  • Process List
    • List of related processes with description of this relation.

Business Actors

Business Actor is a type role that represents someone or something that has an ability to launch Business Use Case. Business Actor is logically connected to a classified user - a human or an automat. Plus4U defines 4 types of users - uuPerson, uuAI, uuEE, uuThing. So, a Business Use-case can be launched by a person, an artificial inteligence, an automat or an IoT Smart Box - but they have to be connected to a proper Business Actor.
On this page, you can find the Business Actors Diagram (not mandatory).
  • From this diagram, it must be clear whether the actor is a business role or a business group.
  • Actors in this diagram are typically logically sorted or grouped (usually in hierarchical order - starting with the actor with the strongest rights). E.g.:
    1. Licence Owner
    2. Order Authories, Order Executives
    3. Customer Authorities, Customer Executives
    4. Customers

Business Actor

What must be filled:
  • Name and description
  • Type (Business Role or Business Group)

Products

A Product virtualizes an entity from the real world. It can be anything from a good to an idea, simply any thing which properties we want to keep track of. From the point of view of a Business Discipline, we can have a product of two types: an Intermediate or a Final product. We call a product Intermediate when a product customer is a process within a given Business Discipline. If the customer is a different Business Discipline or an end customer, we call a product Final product or simply Product.

Product

What must be filled:
  • Name and description
  • Product Flow Classification
    • Each product must have its classification based on relation to the business.
    • There are 3 groups of products:
      • Input product
      • Intermediate product
      • Final product
    • E.g. in process Order creation, I want to create an order for a T-shirt.
      • Input products: eshop
        I need it for order creation - without an e-shop I cannot make an order.
      • Intermediate product: payment, product "T-shirt"
        I need a product that I want to order, and to create a payment for order realisation, but the goal of this process is not payment creation so it is not a final product.
      • Final product: order
        Order was created in this process and it is the final result, which was the goal of this process.
  • uuP Classification
    • Standard - the most common classification.
    • Management - e.g. control panel. A product which serves as a management product.
    • Organizational - e.g. folders, units (sprintlog in uuSprintMan).
    • System - e.g. application itself.
  • Structure
    • Inner structure of the product. Information needed for product description.
    • If the product structure is difficult, the Product's Structure diagram should be added.
    • E.g. product Order needs to have:
      • Code
      • Date of creation
      • Items
      • Price
      • Delivery method
      • Other
    • This structure can be described as a table or commented JavaScript code.  In both cases, there needs to be the name of the attribute, description and real example value. We reccomend to use only one option to describe product structure. Using both may be harder to keep it consistent.
  • Internal Relations
    • Product relations with other products of the same Business Discipline (e.g. relation between Order and Payment).
    • Diagram of Internal Relations is mandatory. Additionally, a list of relations with descriptions can be added.
  • External Relations
    • Product relations with other products from another Business Discipline (e.g. relation to uuBusinessTerritory etc.)
      • Only direct links - e.g. Payment is related to payment from uuPaymentGateway and uuPaymentGateway is related to another Business Discipline, there should be described only the relation to uuPaymentGateway.
    • A diagram of Internal Relations is mandatory. Additionally, a list of the relations with descriptions can be added.
  • State List & Life cycle
    • Each product should have states that represent a summary of circumstances and situations at a particular time or moment.
    • Each state has a name, symbol and description of what this state means or what can be done with the product (e.g. order in state "created" can be paid or cancelled).
      • List of states can be found in Icons (uuBmlDrawg03 - Documentation).
    • Life cycle diagram can be added if the product has a complicated life cycle.
  • Business Use Case List
    • List of Business Use Cases related to this product.

Business Use Cases

Business Use Case is a set of activities performed within a Business Discipline. It is an important part of the Business Discipline methodology and its Business Model. Business Use Case is a part of some Processes of the Business Discipline. Business Use Cases can be launched by Business Actors (Business Role, Business Group) or eventually by another Business Use Cases. (The recursion is allowed.) A Business Use Case deals with the Products (and/or its digital twins) related to the Business Discipline. Generally, a Business Use Case adds value to the Business Discipline Stakeholders. Business Use Case is specified by Happy Day Scenario and Alternative Scenarios. The main purpose of Business Use Case is to be a basis for design and implementation of use-cases in the next automation of Business Discipline.

Business Use Case

What must be filled:
  • Name
    • Preferred name of Business Use Case is always some action (e.g. Order creation or Creation of order. Wrong names: Order create, Customer update etc.)
  • Description
    • Description of the Business Use Case should have some added value. You should provide there important information and avoid descriptions like:
      • "This BUC creates joke."
    • A better way to describe the above mentioned Business Use Case would be:
      • "Without new jokes, our application would not serve its purpose. Operators and Creators are able to create new jokes. In order to create a new joke, name and text or image must be provided."
  • Priority (mandatory; if you are uncertain which one to choose, take a look at MoSCoW Prioritization Categories) and complexity (can be filled later).
  • Trigger List
    • Mandatory section, a list of Business Use Cases and Business Actors, events or particular time that launch the Business Use Case.
    • Additional information about each trigger should be added in its description, for instance how the trigger is launched. Try to keep it universal as the button labels can change over time - The user clicked the "Create item button". vs. The user clicked the button for the item creation.
  • Pre-conditions
    • Mandatory section, a set of conditions that must be met in order to launch the Business Use Case.
    • e.g. The uuJokes workspace exists and is not in a closed state.
  • Post-conditions
    • Mandatory section, a state in which the system will be after the Business Use Case is completed.
    • e.g. The joke has been successfully created and is displayed in the list of jokes.
  • Business Use Case Specification
    • Happy day scenario and alternative scenarios - text description of the flow of activities that need to be done in order to reach a goal.
      • The scenario can contain actions that are not supported by the application, but need to be described for better understanding of business.
      • Happy day scenario must be clearly described including possible alternative scenarios.
      • The name of the message (information, warning and error message) should describe the message clearly and concisely:
        • e.g. Do you really want to quit the joke creation form? All changes that you have made will be lost. vs. Made changes will be lost.
      • The message itself should be comprehensible and user-friendly:
        • e.g. Do you really want to quit the joke creation form? All changes that you have made will be lost.
    • Diagram of scenario (not mandatory) - includes actors who can run this Business Use Case, a process or processes in which the Business Use Case is included, and actions related to products.
      • The same product can appear several times in one diagram (e.g. Order processing - at first, there is order validation, e.g. validation of state, then there is order processing and changing the state of the order - the order appears twice on the diagram, each with different state icon).
    • Diagram and text descriptions describe the same thing, therefore both should contain the same information.
  • Mockups & Wireframes
    • In case of non-trivial visual Business Use Case, this section should contain image and description of elements behaviour and data binding to specific attributes.
      • Filling the Mockups & Wireframes table is mandatory. Should you need some inspiration, check out the uuJokes Update category Business Use Case.
  • Process List
    • List of processes related to this Business Use Case.
    • Each Business Use Case must be related to at least one process.
  • Product List
    • List of products related to this Business Use Case.
    • Each Business Use Case must be related to at least one product.
  • Business Use Case List
    • List of related Business Use Cases.
Happy day scenario vs. alternative scenario

Happy day scenario a description of the actions taken to achieve the stated goal. It ends with the successful achievement of the desired goal, e.g. The system creates the joke.

Alternative scenario extension of the happy day scenario. Description of what could go wrong - unfulfilled conditions (the mandatory attributes were not filled in; name attribute is not unique) or premature termination of the Business Use Case (the user clicked the cancel button on the form).

In case that some section (e.g. pre-conditions or post-conditions) is empty, do not delete it from the page! Instead, leave the section there and add description about it (see the image below).

Business Scenarios

The Business scenario is the algorithm of logical steps for how a particular fictional team reaches the set goal in the given model situation. Generally, at every step, a member of a team (human, artificial intelligence, automat, thing) as Business Actor launches a specific Business Use Case that works with certain Products.
Through Business Scenario, you can describe how to reach the goal using a set of Business Use-cases.
